    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">

Robert L. Frost writes:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="14" relname="span">

&amp;gt;Fine idea. Suggestions? Now that those of us on the left have pretty well
&amp;gt;run the anti-nuclear stuff and eco-feminist stuff pretty hard (to the point
&amp;gt;that the issues are pretty worn and threadbare for media exposure), que
&amp;gt;faire?</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="16" relname="span">

My comment was simply that &quot;political correctness&quot; has been a fairly
effective strategy to use against the academic left and now, apparently, 
against STS as well.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="concession">  Some of it stinks (Byron v.s. Toni Morrison)</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="span"> and
some of it is well grounded (civil liberties, academic freedom). </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="15" relname="span"> We
should be able to use that parts that make sense to our own advantage, rather
than running away from it.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="11" relname="span">

One example is the national cyberspace debates:</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> here issues like the 
clipper chip and information highway on-ramps allow STS-style arguments to 
converge with civil liberties concerns rather than be defending against
them. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="12" relname="span"> I suspect that such convergence could be better adopted in other 
STS areas as well,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> and I wonder if we aren&apos;t in such a habit of defending
against charges of Lysenkoism that we fail to see such opportunities.</segment>
